{"author":{"id":"aed0d72ca16b13a779b1d37a0771f1682d5a59e673ecfbcdd34155713180df84"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1638019041,"nonce":"PtvNf4D5XGZ15O8PKzoG8wy+BqU=","metadata":{"github-id":"I_kwDOD3p2KM4_ezvT","github-url":"https://github.com/OPEN-NEXT/OKH-LOSH/issues/113","origin":"github"},"title":"Image type/description/category","message":"As of now, one can add 0 to many images, referenced with a (repo-)path or URL each.\n\n```toml\nimage = \"img/this-thing.png\"\n```\n\nThere is no way of telling of which nature these images are, or which (if any) fits into a specific context.\nImages may be:\n\n* a logo\n* a technical illustration of the machine\n* a photo that shows a technical detail of the machine\n* a photo that shows a problem with the machine\n* a photo that shows the whole machine in in a specific use-scenario\n* a general photo of the machine, useful for marketing or a web-shop\n* ...\n\nThese are not really interchangeable, and to tell from just the image data which is which, is pretty hard and unreliable.\n\nTherefore, I propose to add some kind of category system, with a set of predefined (in our standard) categories, potentially allowing the users to use custom ones.\nAn image may be in multiple categories, or in none.\n\nIn TOML, it may look like this\n\n```toml\n[[image]]\npath = \"img/this-thing.png\"\ncategories = [\n  \"marketing\",\n  \"shop\",\n]\n```\n\nIn the FabCity Hamburg INTERFACER project, the idea is to use OKH as the OSH project meta-data standard.\nThis though, would be an additional requirement there. \n\nThis is very much related to #105.","files":null}]}